These children are not granted rights to their parents’ property, including as legatees. But, with the emergence of common law marriages, which is rapidly multiplying especially in urban countries, their reality and legal status are firmly bing recognized. For example in South Africa, these are recognized under the Recognition Act, 1959. 17 In Uganda as well, the effects of common law marriages on children born out of wedlock is acknowledged. And in 2010, to protect and empower the children of common law couples, a law was enacted so that children of common law marriage also shared the same rights and benefit with the children of legally married parents. 18 The Civil Registration and Vital Statistics (CRVS) system has a role to play at different levels as its functions cut across both common law and articles and supreme court rulings relating to marriages.
